<section class="mag90" id="first-90-days">
  <h2>First 90 Days in the USA</h2>
  <p class="mag90-intro">Your first three months in the United States set the foundation for your financial future. This <strong>newcomer checklist USA</strong> breaks the first 90 days into clear, week-by-week and month-by-month priorities — from getting your SSN or ITIN and opening a bank account to building credit, understanding health insurance, and filing your first taxes. Follow this <strong>new immigrant USA guide</strong> in order and you will avoid the most common settlement mistakes.</p>
  <div class="mag90-timeline">
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Week 1 &middot; Arrival</span><h3>Get the Essentials in Place</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Apply for your SSN</strong> (Social Security Number) if you are eligible to work — it is free.</li><li><strong>Understand ITIN requirements</strong> if you are not eligible for an SSN but need to bank and file taxes.</li><li><strong>Open a bank account</strong> — many banks accept a passport and ITIN, no SSN required.</li><li><strong>Get a U.S. phone number</strong> with an affordable prepaid or postpaid plan.</li><li><strong>Set up online and mobile banking</strong> so you can pay bills and track spending.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 1 &middot; Settle</span><h3>Find Your Footing</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Secure housing</strong> — arrange short-term then long-term rental accommodation.</li><li><strong>Understand healthcare options</strong> — employer plans, the ACA Marketplace, and Medicaid eligibility.</li><li><strong>Create a realistic budget</strong> based on U.S. living costs in your city.</li><li><strong>Build an emergency fund</strong> covering three to six months of expenses.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 2 &middot; Build</span><h3>Grow Your Stability</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Begin building credit</strong> with a secured or newcomer-friendly credit card.</li><li><strong>Establish payment history</strong> by setting up automatic, on-time bill payments.</li><li><strong>Explore employment opportunities</strong> and have your credentials assessed.</li><li><strong>Register for local services</strong> — library, transit, and community programs.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 3 &middot; Plan</span><h3>Secure Your Future</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Understand U.S. taxes</strong> and your federal and state filing obligations.</li><li><strong>Optimize your banking</strong> — switch to fee-free accounts and high-yield savings.</li><li><strong>Create a long-term financial plan</strong> with 401(k) and IRA basics.</li><li><strong>Review your credit report</strong> from Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion for accuracy.</li></ul></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mag90-callout">
    <div class="mag90-box mag90-tips"><h4>Practical Tips</h4><ul><li>Open your account through a bank's newcomer or ITIN-friendly program to skip the SSN requirement.</li><li>Keep digital and paper copies of your passport, visa, and proof of address — you will need them repeatedly.</li><li>Apply for a secured credit card in week one; it is the fastest way to start a U.S. credit file.</li><li>Start your budget before spending patterns set in, and automate every recurring bill.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-box mag90-mistakes"><h4>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h4><ul><li>Waiting months to apply for credit — the sooner you start, the sooner your score grows.</li><li>Going uninsured by misunderstanding ACA enrollment windows and employer plan deadlines.</li><li>Signing a long lease before understanding the true cost of living in your city.</li><li>Carrying a high credit card balance, which hurts your new credit utilization ratio.</li></ul></div>
  </div>
</section>
